<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Grounds decision
  <a href="/backlog/1862-does-the-workflow-orchestrator-supersede-serial-batch-backlo/">#1862</a> —
  <em>does the Workflow orchestrator supersede the serial <code>batch-backlog-items</code> skill?</em> — a
  front-B currency call under the
  <a href="/backlog/1855-model-usage-watch-keep-claude-s-use-of-the-agent-system-effi/">model-usage watch
  (#1855)</a>. The short answer the survey establishes: <strong>no — they are not competing tools, they are
  two execute modes of one skill</strong>. The deliberation that remains is narrower than the card's framing.
</p>

<h2>The card's premise is false</h2>
<p>
  The card asks the question on the premise that &ldquo;a <code>/workflow</code> skill already exists for
  running backlog items in parallel disjoint lanes, yet <code>batch-backlog-items</code> still runs
  serially.&rdquo; The shipped code says otherwise. There is <strong>no separate <code>/workflow</code>
  skill</strong>:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <code>/workflow</code> (<code>.claude/commands/workflow.md</code>) invokes the <strong>same</strong>
    <code>batch-backlog-items</code> skill in its <code>--parallel</code> execute mode, handing the execute
    phase to the <code>Workflow</code> tool (<code>parallel-execute.workflow.js</code>).
  </li>
  <li>
    <code>/batch</code> and <code>/batch-next</code> are the same skill in its <strong>serial</strong>
    execute mode — the default.
  </li>
  <li>
    The conversational arc is <strong>identical</strong> across modes (pack &rarr; ordered plan &rarr; one
    &ldquo;go&rdquo; &rarr; reserve &rarr; close-out); only the execute phase differs. <code>--parallel</code>
    / <code>--serial</code> flip either command per-invocation.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  So the relationship the card asks us to decide is <strong>already shipped and coherent</strong> (delivered
  under epic <a href="/backlog/1143-safe-parallel-batching-via-workflow-orchestration/">#1143</a> /
  <a href="/backlog/1147-workflow-driven-batch-parallel-effects-manifest-serial-integ/">#1147</a>): one skill,
  serial default, parallel opt-in, <strong>auto-degenerating to serial</strong> when no provably-disjoint
  lane exists.
</p>

<h2>Standing test — the &ldquo;supersede?&rdquo; question is a confirmation, not a fork</h2>
<p>
  Against the fork-existence test, the card's three options collapse:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>(a) keep both</strong> and <strong>(c) serial default + opt-in</strong> both
    <em>describe the shipped reality</em> &mdash; a support-both confirmation, not a fork.</li>
  <li><strong>(b) fold batching into Workflow (always parallel)</strong> is the
    <strong>excluded / broken branch</strong>: tightly-coupled items can't be safely parallelized (overlapping
    touch-sets &rarr; worktree merge conflicts), and the orchestrator <em>already</em> routes those to the
    serial lane. Forcing always-parallel adds probe + worktree overhead and bimodal calibration noise with
    <strong>zero</strong> throughput benefit when items are coupled. A named-broken branch &rArr; ratify
    against it.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What remains worth ratifying — two residuals</h2>
<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>Routing / entry model</strong> (a genuine fork): keep <strong>explicit</strong> mode selection
    (serial <code>/batch</code> default, parallel <code>/workflow</code> opt-in) vs. an
    <strong>auto-routing</strong> single entry that probes disjointness and picks per item. Both branches are
    coherent and mutually exclusive as the default. Recommended default (post-skeptic) =
    <strong>(b) auto-route</strong>: the orchestrator's probe <em>already</em> makes the serial-vs-parallel
    call at item granularity, and <code>calibrate()</code> is mode-blind, so the clean-estimate guarantee is
    prose-enforced not code-enforced &mdash; an auto-router can code-gate the calibration-skip on
    &ldquo;did any lane run concurrent,&rdquo; with <code>--serial</code>/<code>--parallel</code> retained as
    overrides. Residual the decider weighs: unifying on the orchestrator makes every batch pay probe +
    worktree overhead and lose the inline-serial calibrated path.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Structured-output (<code>agent({schema})</code>) adoption</strong> (the card's downstream note)
    &mdash; <em>dissolves to supported-by-default, not a fork</em>. Schema is <strong>already adopted</strong>
    across the orchestrator's lanes (<code>PROBE_SCHEMA</code>, item-result, integrate, replay); the
    compounding probe&rarr;partition step the 0.95<sup>N</sup> argument describes is already validated, and
    fork pre-flight is reserved <strong>main-loop human judgment</strong>, not a lane handoff. The readiness
    ranker (<code>scripts/check-readiness.mjs</code>) stays LLM-free as a <strong>determinism /
    CLI-tab-parity invariant</strong>. The only follow-on is hardening <code>PROBE_SCHEMA</code> validation.
  </li>
</ol>

<h2>External prior art</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Serial-vs-parallel is an explicit author choice in the field.</strong> CrewAI exposes
    <code>Process.sequential</code> / <code>hierarchical</code> as a declared crew property; LangGraph models
    execution as an explicit directed state-graph with conditional edges. Neither <em>infers</em> the
    execution shape &mdash; the operator declares it. Supports the explicit-default for residual 1.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Structured output beats free-text parsing, and the gain compounds along a chain.</strong>
    Provider-native schema enforcement (tool-calling under the hood) yields near-deterministic parse success;
    free-text JSON parsing fails a few percent per step, and a 10-step chain at 95%/step completes only
    &asymp;60% of the time. The case for <code>agent({schema})</code> is strongest where output feeds
    downstream (the parallel lanes) and weakest where the path is <em>already</em> deterministic (the ranker).
  </li>
</ul>

